  "local_port": 45520,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Do you think the promise made by BJP of giving 15 lakhs to every Indians account will be true?",
  "response": "The promise you're referring to was made by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) during the 2014 Indian general election campaign. Narendra Modi, the then-prime ministerial candidate, stated that if elected, his government would recover black money stashed abroad and deposit 15 lakhs (1.5 million) Indian Rupees into every Indian's bank account.\n\nHowever, this promise has not been fulfilled, and it is highly unlikely that it will be fulfilled in the future. There are several reasons for this:\n\n1. **Practicality**: The amount of black money stashed abroad is difficult to estimate accurately, and even if it were possible to recover it, the total amount would not be sufficient to deposit 15 lakhs into every Indian's bank account. India has a population of over 1.4 billion people, and distributing such a large sum to every citizen would be logistically challenging.\n\n2. **Legal and diplomatic hurdles**: Recovering black money from foreign countries involves complex legal and diplomatic processes. It would require cooperation from the governments of those countries, which may not always be forthcoming.\n\n3. **Change in stance**: Over time, BJP leaders, including Narendra Modi, have distanced themselves from this promise. They have clarified that the statement was made in a figurative sense and not as a literal policy commitment.\n\nIn conclusion, while the promise of depositing 15 lakhs into every Indian's bank account was a significant talking point during the 2014 election campaign, it is not a realistic or achievable goal. It is essential to consider such promises in the context of their feasibility and the government's subsequent actions and statements.",
